    Was Munch an impressionist?
    Norwegian artist Edvard Munch (18631944), like other Symbolist artists and writers throughout Europe in the 1890s, rejected the Impressionist practice of studying the effects of light on the exterior world and instead looked inward to explore themes of love and jealousy, loneliness and anxiety, sickness and death.

    Search for: Was Munch an impressionist?
    Why is Munch so famous?
    Edvard Munch was a world-famous painter and printmaker from Norway. Born in Lten in 1863, Munch was active for more than 60 years and was one of Modernism's most important artists. His best-known work is The Scream, painted in 1893, which is one of the most iconic paintings in modern art.

    Is Munch an Expressionist?
    The Norwegian painter Edvard Munch (18631944) is the founder of modern expressionism. This great and lonely artist, who was so completely absorbed in his work, has been appreciated at his real importance only by a handful of initiated people in the West.Feb 26, 2016

    About

    Description

    Edvard Munch was a Norwegian painter. His best known work, The Scream, has become one of Western art's most iconic images. His childhood was overshadowed by illness, bereavement and the dread of inheriting a mental condition that ran in the family. Wikipedia
    Born: December 12, 1863, dalsbruk, Norway
    Died: January 23, 1944, Oslo, Norway
    Periods: Expressionism, Modern art, Symbolism, Post-Impressionism
    Series: The Scream, The Sick Child, Melancholy
    Nationality: Norwegian
    Parents: Laura Catherine Bjlstad, Christian Munch
